#: ../../source/introduction.rst:2
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr "介绍"

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:4
msgid ""
"Nest is a framework for building efficient, scalable `Node.js "
"<https://nodejs.org/>`__ server-side applications. It uses progressive "
"JavaScript, is built with and fully supports `TypeScript "
"<http://www.typescriptlang.org/>`__ (yet still enables developers to code"
" in pure JavaScript) and combines elements of OOP (Object Oriented "
"Programming), FP (Functional Programming), and FRP (Functional Reactive "
"Programming)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:12
msgid ""
"Under the hood, Nest makes use of robust HTTP Server frameworks like "
"`Express <https://expressjs.com/>`__ (the default) and `Fastify "
"<https://github.com/fastify/fastify>`__. Nest provides a level of "
"abstraction above these frameworks, but can also expose their APIs "
"directly to the developer. This allows for easy use of the myriad third-"
"party modules which are available for each platform."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:20
msgid "Philosophy"
msgstr "Philosophy"

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:22
msgid ""
"In recent years, thanks to Node.js, JavaScript has become the “lingua "
"franca” of the web for both front and backend applications. This has "
"given rise to awesome projects like `Angular <https://angular.io/>`__, "
"`React <https://github.com/facebook/react>`__ and `Vue "
"<https://github.com/vuejs/vue>`__, which improve developer productivity "
"and enable the construction of fast, testable, and extensible frontend "
"applications. However, while plenty of superb libraries, helpers, and "
"tools exist for Node (and server-side JavaScript), none of them "
"effectively solve the main problem - **architecture**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:33
msgid ""
"Nest provides an out-of-the-box application architecture which allows "
"developers and teams to create highly testable, scalable, loosely "
"coupled, and easily maintainable applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:38
msgid "Installation"
msgstr "Installation"

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:40
msgid ""
"To get started, you can either scaffold the project with the `Nest CLI "
"</cli/overview>`__, or clone a starter project (both will produce the "
"same outcome)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:44
msgid ""
"To scaffold the project with the Nest CLI, run the following commands. "
"This will create a new project directory, and populate the directory with"
" the initial core Nest files and supporting modules, creating a "
"conventional base structure for your project. Creating a new project with"
" the **Nest CLI** is recommended for first-time users. We’ll continue "
"with this approach in `First Steps <first-steps>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:56
msgid "Alternatively, to install the TypeScript starter project with **Git**:"
msgstr "Alternatively, to install the TypeScript starter project with **Git**:"

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:65
msgid ""
"To install the JavaScript flavor of the starter project, use "
"``javascript-starter.git`` in the command sequence above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/introduction.rst:68
msgid ""
"You can also manually create a new project from scratch by installing the"
" core and supporting files with **npm** (or **yarn**). In this case, of "
"course, you’ll be responsible for creating the project boilerplate files "
"yourself."
msgstr ""

